or@rgb@fill{0}{0}{0}\pgfsys@invoke{ }\hbox{{${e}$}} }}\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope}}} } \pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope{}{}{}\hss}% \pgfsys@discardpath\pgfsys@invoke{\lxSVG@closescope }\pgfsys@endscope\hss}% \lxSVG@closescope\endpgfpicture}},$ such that $E$ is the associated admissible equivalence relation and $[\varphi]$ the associated class of compatible actions.
Definition 2.1. A split extension ${N}$${G}$${H}$${k}$${e}$${s}$ is weakly Schreier if for each $g\in G$ there exists a (not necessarily unique) $n\in N$ such that $g=k(n)se(g)$.
Definition 4.11. A map $g\colon H\times H\to N$ is a factor set with respect to an admissible equivalence relation $E$ and a compatible action $\varphi$ if $g(x,1)=1=g(1,x)$ and $(g(x,y)g(xy,z),xyz)\sim(\varphi(x,g(y,z))g(x,yz),xyz).$
Definition 2. Consider $\vec{a}\in A^{n}$ and $\vec{b}\in B^{n}$. So two $\sigma_{n}$-structures $\mathfrak{A},\mathfrak{B}$ are $d$-equivalents under $k$-homotopic equivalence if, and only if, there is a bijection $f:A\rightarrow B$ such that $N_{d}^{\mathfrak{A}}(\vec{a}c)\sim_{k}N_{d}^{\mathfrak{B}}(\vec{b}f(c))$, for every $c\in A$. When this occurs, I denote this fact by $(\mathfrak{A},\vec{a})\leftrightarrows_{(d,\sim_{k})}(\mathfrak{B},\vec{b})$. If $n=0$, we have to satisfy only the condition that there is a bijection $f:A\rightarrow B$ such that $N_{d}^{\mathfrak{A}}(c)\sim_{k}N_{d}^{\mathfrak{B}}(f(c))$, for every $c\in A$, and the denotation is simply $\mathfrak{A}\leftrightarrows_{(d,\sim_{k})}\mathfrak{B}$.
Definition 4 (Hanf-locality under $\sim_{k}$-equivalence). An $m$-ary query $Q$ on $\sigma$-structures is Hanf-local under $\sim_{k}$-equivalence if there exists a number $d\geq 0$ such that for every $\mathfrak{A},\mathfrak{B}\in\mathrm{STRUCT}[\sigma]$, $(\mathfrak{A},\vec{a})\leftrightarrows_{(d,\sim_{k})}(\mathfrak{B},\vec{b})% \textrm{ implies }(\vec{a}\in Q(\mathfrak{A})\Leftrightarrow\vec{b}\in Q(% \mathfrak{B})).$ The smallest $d$ for which the above condition holds is called the Hanf-locality rank of $Q$ under $\sim_{k}$-equivalence, and is denoted by $\mathsf{hlr}_{\sim_{k}}(Q)$.
Definition 1. A structure $\mathfrak{A}$ is $k$-extendable if, for every set $X\subseteq A$ of size $<k$ and every structure $\mathfrak{B}$ such that $\mathfrak{A}\rightleftarrows_{X}^{k-|X|}\mathfrak{B}$, it holds that $\forall b\in B\textrm{ }\exists a\in A$ s.t. $\mathfrak{A}\rightleftarrows_{X}^{k-|X|-1}\mathfrak{B}$.
Definition 3 (Gaifman-locality under $\sim_{k}$-equivalence). An $m$-ary query $Q$, $m>0$, on $\sigma_{n}$-structures, is called Gaifman-local under $\sim_{k}$-equivalence if there exists a number $d\geq 0$ such that for every $\sigma$-structure $\mathfrak{A}$ and every $\vec{a}_{1},\vec{a}_{2}\in A^{m}$, $N_{d}^{\mathfrak{A}}(\vec{a}_{1})\sim_{k}N_{d}^{\mathfrak{A}}(\vec{a}_{2})% \textrm{ implies }(\vec{a}_{1}\in Q(\mathfrak{A})\Leftrightarrow\vec{a}_{2}\in Q% (\mathfrak{A})).$ The minimum $d$ for which the above condition holds is called the Gaifman-locality rank of $Q$ under $\sim_{k}$-equivalence, and is denoted by $\mathsf{lr}_{\sim_{k}}(Q)$.
Definition 3.7. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ and ${\mathcal{D}}$ be ${\mathcal{Q}}$-categories. (1) A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $f\colon{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{D}}$ is a function $f\colon{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}\longrightarrow{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{D}})}$ such that for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{C}}$, ${\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime})\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}{\mathcal{D}}(f(c),f(c^{\prime% }))$ holds. (2) A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functor $f\colon{\mathcal{C}}\longrightarrow{\mathcal{D}}$ is fully faithful if for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{C}}$, (3) is satisfied with equality. We call fully faithful ${\mathcal{Q}}$-functors embeddings for short.
Definition 5.1 ([AHRT02, Definitions 2.1]). (1) An object $E$ of ${\mathcal{X}}$ is injective if, whenever we have objects $C$ and $D$, a morphism $f\colon C\longrightarrow D$, and an embedding $i\colon C\longrightarrow D$, there exists a (not necessarily unique) morphism $g\colon D\longrightarrow E$ such that $f=g\circ i$. (2) A morphism $f\colon C\longrightarrow D$ in ${\mathcal{X}}$ is called an essential embedding if: (i) $f$ is an embedding, and (ii) for any object $E$ and morphism $g\colon D\longrightarrow E$, if $g\circ f$ is an embedding then so is $g$. (3) An injective envelope of an object ${C}$ of ${\mathcal{X}}$ is a pair $(D,f)$ consisting of an injective object $D$ and an essential embedding $f\colon{C}\longrightarrow{D}$.
Definition 3.1. A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category ${\mathcal{C}}$ consists of: (CD1): a set ${\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$ of objects; (CD2): for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$, an element ${\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime})\in{Q}$ satisfying the following axioms: (CA1): for each $c\in{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$, $I_{\mathcal{Q}}\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}{\mathcal{C}}(c,c)$; (CA2): for each $c,c^{\prime},c^{\prime\prime}\in{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$, ${\mathcal{C}}(c^{\prime},c^{\prime\prime})\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}{\mathcal{C}}(c,c% ^{\prime})\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}{\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime\prime})$. We also write $c\in{\mathcal{C}}$ for $c\in{\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})}$.
Definition 2.1. A (unital) quantale ${\mathcal{Q}}$ is a complete lattice $(Q,\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}})$ equipped with a monoid structure $(Q,I_{\mathcal{Q}},\circ_{\mathcal{Q}})$ such that the multiplication $\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}$ preserves arbitrary suprema in each variable: $(\bigvee_{i\in I}y_{i})\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}x=\bigvee_{i\in I}(y_{i}\circ_{% \mathcal{Q}}x)$ and $y\circ_{\mathcal{Q}}(\bigvee_{i\in I}x_{i})=\bigvee_{i\in I}(y\circ_{\mathcal{% Q}}x_{i})$. We often omit the subscript ${\mathcal{Q}}$ from the data of a quantale, writing it simply as ${\mathcal{Q}}=(Q,\preceq,I,\circ)$.
Definition 3.6 ([Stu06a, Section 2]). A ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is said to be: • powered if for any $c\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and $x\in Q$, the power $x\pitchfork c$ exists in ${\mathcal{C}}$; • copowered if for any $c\in{\mathcal{C}}$ and $x\in Q$, the copower $x\ast c$ exists in ${\mathcal{C}}$; • order-complete if the preordered set $({\mathrm{ob}({\mathcal{C}})},\preceq_{\mathcal{C}})$ is complete (i.e., if its poset reflection1The poset reflection of a preordered set $(P,\preceq)$ is the quotient of it by the equivalence relation $\preceq\cap\succeq$. is a complete lattice); and • complete if it is powered, copowered and order-complete.
Definition 4.1 (Cf. [Stu05, Proposition 6.1]). Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category. The ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category $\mathcal{P}{\mathcal{C}}$ of presheaves over ${\mathcal{C}}$ is defined as follows. • An object is a presheaf over ${\mathcal{C}}$, that is a family $P=(Pc)_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}$ of elements of ${Q}$ satisfying the inequality $Pc^{\prime}\circ{\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime})\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}Pc$ for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{C}}$. • The element $\mathcal{P}{\mathcal{C}}(P,P^{\prime})$ of ${Q}$ is given by $\bigwedge_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}P^{\prime}c\mathbin{\swarrow}Pc$. Dually, the ${\mathcal{Q}}$-category $\mathcal{P}^{\dagger}{\mathcal{C}}$ of copresheaves over ${\mathcal{C}}$ is defined as follows. • An object is a copresheaf over ${\mathcal{C}}$, that is a family $R=(Rc)_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}$ of elements of ${Q}$ satisfying the inequality ${\mathcal{C}}(c,c^{\prime})\circ Rc\preceq_{\mathcal{Q}}Rc^{\prime}$ for each $c,c^{\prime}\in{\mathcal{C}}$. • The element $\mathcal{P}^{\dagger}{\mathcal{C}}(R,R^{\prime})$ of ${Q}$ is given by $\bigwedge_{c\in{\mathcal{C}}}R^{\prime}c\mathbin{\searrow}Rc$.
Definition 2.1. A $({\mathcal{D}},{\mathcal{C}})-$bimodule category ${\mathcal{M}}$ is invertible if there exists a $({\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{D}})$-bimodule category ${\mathcal{N}}$ such that ${\mathcal{M}}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{C}}{\mathcal{N}}\simeq{\mathcal{D}},\quad{% \mathcal{N}}\boxtimes_{\mathcal{D}}{\mathcal{M}}\simeq{\mathcal{C}},$ as bimodule categories.
Definition 5.2. A $V$-category $(X,a)$ is said to be regular if $a\cdot a^{\circ}\leq a$, which is equivalent to $a=a^{\circ}$, that is, it is symmetric. Indeed, regularity means that, for all $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}\in X$, one has $a(x_{1},x_{2})\otimes a(x_{1},x_{3})\leq a(x_{2},x_{3})$. Clearly, if $(X,a)$ is symmetric, then this condition is satisfied. Conversely, from regularity one obtains, choosing $x_{1}=x_{3}$: $a(x_{3},x_{2})=a(x_{3},x_{2})\otimes k\leq a(x_{3},x_{2})\otimes a(x_{3},x_{3}% )\leq a(x_{2},x_{3})\quad\text{for all}\ x_{2},x_{3}\in X.$
Definition 6.3 ([23]). An object $Y$ of a pointed, finitely complete category ${\rm\bf C}$ is (1) a strongly unital object if the point $\xymatrix{Y\times Y\ar@<-2pt>[r]_{-}{\pi_{2}}&Y\ar@<-2pt>[l]_{-}{\langle 1,1% \rangle}}$ is stably strong; (2) a Mal’tsev object if, for every pullback of split epimorphisms over $Y$ as in the following diagram \xymatrix @!0@=5em A×_YZ \ar@¡-.5ex¿[d]_π_A \ar@¡-.5ex¿[r]_(.7)π_Z & Z \ar@¡-.5ex¿[d]_g \ar@¡-.5ex¿[l]_-⟨sg,1_Z ⟩ A \ar@¡-.5ex¿[u]_(.4)⟨1_A,tf ⟩ \ar@¡-.5ex¿[r]_f & Y, \ar@¡-.5ex¿[l]_s \ar@¡-.5ex¿[u]_t the morphisms $\langle 1_{A},tf\rangle$ and $\langle sg,1_{Z}\rangle$ are jointly strongly epimorphic; (3) a protomodular object if every point over $Y$ is stably strong.
Definition 5.1. A $V$-functor $f\colon(X,a)\to(Y,b)$ is proper if $b\cdot f\leq f\cdot a$, while it is open if $b^{\circ}\cdot f\leq f\cdot a^{\circ}$.
Definition 6.2. A point (i.e. a split epimorphism with a fixed section) $\xymatrix{A\ar@<-2pt>[r]_{f}&Y\ar@<-2pt>[l]_{s}}$ with kernel $n\colon X\to A$ in a pointed finitely complete category is strong if $n$ and $s$ are jointly strongly epimorphic. It is stably strong if every pullback of it along any morphism $g\colon Z\to Y$ is strong.
Definition 3.5. [12, Subsection 4.3] Let $S$ be an inverse semigroup. A map $\nu:S\to S$ is called a nucleus if it satisfies the following conditions: (N1) $a\leq\nu(a)$ for all $a\in S$. (N2) $a\leq b$ implies that $\nu(a)\leq\nu(b)$. (N3) $\nu^{2}(a)=\nu(a)$ for all $a\in S$. (N4) $\nu(a)\nu(b)\leq\nu(ab)$ for all $a,b\in S$.
Definition 4.1. Let $S$ be an inverse semigroup and $F\subseteq E(S)$ a filter in $E(S)$. Let $s\in S$ be such that $ss^{-1}\in F$. The germ of $s$ at $F$ is the set $\text{germ}_{F}\,s=\{t\in S\mid tt^{-1}\in F\text{ and }ft=fs\text{ for some }% f\in F\}.$
Definition 3.1. Let $S$ be a inverse semigroup and $\mathcal{C}=\{\mathcal{C}(a)\}_{a\in S}$ be a family where $\mathcal{C}(a)$ is a set of subsets of $\downarrow\hskip-2.845276pt{a}$. We say that $\mathcal{C}$ is a coverage on $S$ if for every $a,b\in S$ and $X\in\mathcal{C}(a)$, we have that $bX\in\mathcal{C}(ba)$ and $Xb\in\mathcal{C}(ab)$. In this case, the elements of $\mathcal{C}(a)$ are called coverings of $a$. And we say that $\mathcal{C}$ is a strong coverage if the following conditions are satisfied: (R) $\{a\}\in\mathcal{C}(a)$ for all $a\in S$. (I) If $X\in\mathcal{C}(a)$ then $X^{-1}\in\mathcal{C}(a^{-1})$. (MS) If $X\in\mathcal{C}(a)$ and $Y\in\mathcal{C}(b)$ then $XY\in\mathcal{C}(ab)$. (T) If $X\in\mathcal{C}(a)$ and $X_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(x_{i})$ for each $x_{i}\in X$ then $\bigcup_{i}X_{i}\in\mathcal{C}(a)$.
Definition 3.4. Let $S$ be an inverse semigroup and $\mathcal{C}$ a coverage on $S$. A semigroup homomorphism $\theta:S\to T$ to a pseudogroup $T$ is called a $\mathcal{C}$-cover-to-join map if for every $a\in S$ and $X\in\mathcal{C}(a)$, we have that $\theta(a)=\bigvee_{x\in X}\theta(x).$
Definition 2.3. 1. A category $I$ is direct if it admits a functor $\deg:I\to\mathbb{N}$ that reflects identities, where $\mathbb{N}$ is equipped with the usual order. Let $I$ be a direct category. 2. Let $i\in I$, then the latching category $\partial(I\downarrow i)$ is the full subcategory of the slice category $I\downarrow i$ without the object $\operatorname{id}_{i}$. 3. Let $i\in I$ and $X:I\to\mathcal{C}$, then the latching object $L_{i}X$ is (if it exists) a colimit of $\tikzcd[columnsep=1.25cm]\partial(I\downarrow i)\ar{r}{\text{source}}&I\ar{r}{% X}&\mathcal{C}.$ The latching map is the canonical map $L_{i}X\to X$ induced by the inclusion $\partial(I\downarrow i)\hookrightarrow(I\downarrow i).$ 4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a cofibration category. A diagram $X:I\to\mathcal{C}$ is Reedy cofibrant if for every $i\in I$ is the latching object $L_{i}X$ exists and the latching map is a cofibration. 5. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a cofibration category. A natural transformation $f:X\to Y$ between Reedy cofibrant diagrams $X\to Y$ is a Reedy cofibration if for all $i\in I$ the induced map $X(i)\sqcup_{L_{i}X}L_{i}Y\longrightarrow Y(i)$ is a cofibration. 6. A map $I\to J$ of (small) categories is a sieve if it is injective on objects, fully faithful and closed under precomposition.
Definition 3.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a dg-category. The cycle category $\mathcal{C}_{0}$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is the category with the same objects as $\mathcal{C}$ and morphisms given by $0$-cycles of the mapping complexes: $\operatorname{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}_{0}}(X,Y)=\{f\in{\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{% C}}(X,Y)}_{0}\mid df=0\}.$ The homology category $H(\mathcal{C})$ of $\mathcal{C}$ is the category with the same objects as $\mathcal{C}$ and morphisms given by the homology of the mapping complexes in degree $0$: $\operatorname{Hom}_{H(\mathcal{C})}(X,Y)=H_{0}(\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}% }(X,Y)).$
Definition 4.2. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a dg-category, $(X,f)$ an $n$-simplex of $\operatorname{N}_{\operatorname{dg}}(\mathcal{C})$ and $\alpha\in D[n]$. Then let $C(X,f)(\alpha)$ denote the $\mathcal{C}$-module defined by the graded abelian group $C(X,f)(\alpha)=\prod_{i\in D[n]\downarrow\alpha}\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C% }}(X_{(\alpha\circ i)(0)},-)\subseteq\operatorname{Map}_{\operatorname{Ch}}(% \operatorname{Cell}(\alpha),\oplus_{X\in\mathcal{C}}\operatorname{Map}_{% \mathcal{C}}(X,-))$ together with the differential that sends homogeneous elements $\varphi\in C(X,f)(\alpha)$ to $d_{f}\varphi:=d\varphi-{(-1)}^{|\varphi|}\varphi*f,$ where $d$ is the differential of the underlying mapping space. By functoriality of $\operatorname{Cell}$, this definition extends to a functor from $D[n]^{\operatorname{op}}$ to $\mathcal{C}$-modules.
Definition 2.2. A cofibration category is a homotopical category $\mathcal{C}$ equipped additionally with a class of morphisms called cofibrations (where an acyclic cofibration is a morphism that is both a cofibration and a weak equivalence) such that: 1. All isomorphisms are acyclic cofibrations. Cofibrations are stable under composition. The category $\mathcal{C}$ has an initial object and every morphism from the initial object is a cofibration. 2. Cofibrations and acyclic cofibrations are closed under pushouts. 3. Every morphism in $\mathcal{C}$ can be factored as the composite of a cofibration followed by a weak equivalence.
Definition 3.12. For $n\geq 0$, define $\operatorname{Path}(n)$ to be the dg-coalgebra that as a graded abelian group is given in degree $k>0$ by the freely generated abelian group ${\operatorname{Path}(n)}_{k}=\mathbb{Z}\cdot\{\alpha:[k]\to[n]\}$ and which vanishes in degrees $k\leq 0$. The differential of $\operatorname{Path}(n)$ sends a homogeneous element $\alpha:[k]\to[n]$ to the alternating sum of its inner faces: $d\langle\alpha_{0},\ldots,\alpha_{k}\rangle=\sum_{j=1}^{k-1}{(-1)}^{j}\langle% \alpha_{0},\ldots,\hat{\alpha_{j}},\ldots,\alpha_{k}\rangle.$ The comultiplication $\Delta:\operatorname{Path}(n)\to\operatorname{Path}(n)\otimes\operatorname{% Path}(n)$ splits sequences: $\Delta\langle\alpha_{0},\ldots,\alpha_{k}\rangle=\sum_{j=1}^{k-1}{(-1)}^{j(k-j% )}\langle\alpha_{j},\ldots,\alpha_{k}\rangle\otimes\langle\alpha_{0},\ldots,% \alpha_{j}\rangle.$
Definition 2.7 ([Szu14]). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a cofibration category. The quasicategory of frames $\operatorname{N}_{\operatorname{f}}(\mathcal{C})$ is the simplicial set where ${\operatorname{N}_{\operatorname{f}}(\mathcal{C})}_{n}$ is the set of homotopical, Reedy cofibrant diagrams $D[n]\to\mathcal{C}$ and simplicial maps are induced by precomposition.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a dg-category. The $n$-translation of an object $X\in\mathcal{C}$ for some $n\in\mathbb{Z}$ is an object $X[n]\in\mathcal{C}$ representing the $n$-translated mapping complex: $\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(X[n],-)\cong\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(% X,-)[-n].$ The mapping cone of a $0$-cycle $f:X\to Y$ is an object $\operatorname{Cone}(f)$ representing the mapping cone of the induced map on mapping complexes: $\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(\operatorname{Cone}(f),-)\cong\operatorname{% Cone}(f^{*}:\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,-)\to\operatorname{Map}_{% \mathcal{C}}(Y,-)).$ A dg-category $\mathcal{C}$ is pretriangulated if it has a zero object, it admits translations of all objects, and it admits mapping cones for all $0$-cycles.
Definition 2.1. A homotopical category is a category $\mathcal{C}$ together with a collection of morphisms called weak equivalences that contains all identity morphisms and satisfies the 2-out-of-6 property: If $\tikzcd W\ar{r}{f}&X\ar{r}{g}&Y\ar{r}{h}&Z$ is a composable sequence in $\mathcal{C}$ where $h\circ g$ and $g\circ f$ are weak equivalences, then $f$, $g$, $h$, and $h\circ g\circ f$ are weak equivalences as well. A functor between homotopical categories is homotopical if it preserves weak equivalences.
Definition 3.5. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a pretriangulated dg-category. A $0$-cycle $i:X\to Y$ is a cofibration if the precomposition map $i^{*}:\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(Y,-)\longrightarrow\operatorname{Map}_{% \mathcal{C}}(X,-)$ is surjective as a map of $\mathcal{C}$-modules and has a representable kernel.
Definition 4.1. For an object $\alpha\in D[n]$ define $\operatorname{Cell}(\alpha)$ to be the $\operatorname{Path}(n)$-comodule that in degree $k\geq 0$ is the free abelian group ${\operatorname{Cell}(\alpha)}_{k}=\mathbb{Z}\cdot\{(i:\beta\hookrightarrow% \alpha)\in(D[n]\downarrow\alpha)\mid\beta:[k]\to[n]\}$ together with the differential $d^{*}\langle i_{0},\ldots,i_{k}\rangle=\sum_{j=1}^{k}{(-1)}^{j}\langle i_{0},% \ldots,\hat{i_{j}},\ldots,i_{k}\rangle,$ and the comultiplication $\delta:\operatorname{Cell}(\alpha)\to\operatorname{Cell}(\alpha)\otimes% \operatorname{Path}(n)$ $\delta\langle i_{0},\ldots,i_{k}\rangle=\sum_{j=1}^{k}{(-1)}^{j(k-j)}\langle i% _{j},\ldots,i_{k}\rangle\otimes(\alpha\circ\langle i_{0},\ldots,i_{j}\rangle).$ By postcomposition this definition extends to a functor from $D[n]$ to $\operatorname{Path}(n)$-comodules.
Definition 3.1. A dg-category is a category enriched in the category of chain complexes, i.e. a dg-category $\mathcal{C}$ consists of: 1. A collection of objects $\operatorname{Ob}{\mathcal{C}}$, 2. a chain complex $\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)$ for all $X,Y\in\operatorname{Ob}{\mathcal{C}}$, 3. a chain map $\circ:\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(Y,Z)\otimes\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal% {C}}(X,Y)\to\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Z)$, for all $X,Y,Z\in\operatorname{Ob}{\mathcal{C}}$, and 4. an element $\operatorname{id}_{X}\in{\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,X)}_{0}$ for all $X\in\operatorname{Ob}{\mathcal{C}}$, such that $\circ$ is associative and the elements $\operatorname{id}_{X}$ are the identity elements of $\circ$. A dg-functor $F$ between dg-categories $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ is a functor $\mathcal{C}\to\mathcal{D}$ of enriched categories.
Definition 2.6 ([Szu14]). Let $I$ be a homotopical category, then $DI$ is the category with objects given by functors $[m]\to I$ and morphisms between $\varphi:[m]\to I$ and $\psi:[n]\to I$ given by injective maps $\sigma:[m]\hookrightarrow[n]$ such that $\varphi=\psi\circ\sigma$. The forgetful functor $DI\to I$ sends $x:[n]\to I$ to $x(n)$ and creates weak equivalences in $DI$, making $DI$ into a homotopical category.
Definition 3.3. Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a dg-category. A map $f:X\to Y$ in the cycle category $\mathcal{C}_{0}$ is a weak equivalence, if it becomes an isomorphism in the homology category.
Definition 3.9 ([Fao17]). Let $\mathcal{C}$ be a dg-category. The dg-nerve $\operatorname{N}_{\operatorname{dg}}(\mathcal{C})$ is the simplicial set where an $n$-simplex consists of a family of objects $X_{0},\ldots,X_{n}$ together with a family of maps: 1. For each sequence $\langle i_{0},\ldots,i_{k}\rangle:[k]\to[n]$ with $k>0$ there is a chosen map $f(\langle i_{0},\ldots,i_{k}\rangle)\in{\operatorname{Map}_{\mathcal{C}}(X_{i_% {0}},X_{i_{k}})}_{k-1}$ 2. The maps satisfy a differential coherence condition: $\displaystyle-df(\langle i_{0},\ldots,i_{k}\rangle)$ $\displaystyle=\sum_{j=1}^{k-1}{(-1)}^{j}f(\langle i_{0},\ldots,\hat{i_{j}},% \ldots,i_{k}\rangle)$ $\displaystyle+\sum_{j=1}^{k-1}{(-1)}^{(j-1)k}f(\langle i_{j},\ldots,i_{k}% \rangle)\circ f(\langle i_{0},\ldots,i_{j}\rangle),$ 3. The maps satisfy strict unitality: $\displaystyle f(\langle i_{0},i_{1}\rangle)$ $\displaystyle=\operatorname{id}_{X_{i_{0}}}$ $\displaystyle\qquad\text{(if $i_{0}=i_{1}$)}$ $\displaystyle f(\langle i_{0},\ldots,i_{k}\rangle)$ $\displaystyle=0$ $\displaystyle\qquad\text{(if $i_{j}=i_{j+1}$ for some $j$)}.$ An order-preserving map $\alpha:[m]\to[n]$ acts on such an $m$-simplex by reindexing the objects and by precomposition of the sequences.
Definition B.2. A planar graph between two real numbers $a<b$ is a finite topological graph $\Gamma$ embedded in $\mathbb{R}\times[a,b]$ such that every $x\in\Gamma\cap(\mathbb{R}\times\set{a,b})$ is a node in $\Gamma_{0}$ and belongs to the closure of exactly one edge in $\Gamma_{1}$.
Definition 2.1. A (strict) monoidal category is a category $\mathbf{C}$ equipped with an associative and unital functor $\otimes:\mathbf{C}\times\mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{C}$ for $\times$ the Cartesian product. A (strict) premonoidal category is a category $\mathbf{C}$ equipped with an associative and unital functor $\boxtimes:\mathbf{C}\ \Box\ \mathbf{C}\to\mathbf{C}$ for $\Box$ given by the following pushout in $\mathbf{Cat}$: {tikzcd} & C_0 ×D_0 \arrow[r, ""] \arrow[d, ""] & C ×D_0 \arrow[d, ""] & C_0 ×D \arrow[r, ""] & C □ D where $\mathbf{C}_{0},\mathbf{D}_{0}$ are the discrete category of objects and the maps are given by the inclusions.
Definition B.1. A topological graph, also called 1d cell complex, is a tuple $(\Gamma,\Gamma_{0},\Gamma_{1})$ of a Hausdorff space $\Gamma$ and a closed, discrete subset $\Gamma_{0}\subseteq\Gamma$ of nodes such that $\Gamma-\Gamma_{0}=\coprod\Gamma_{1}$ is the sum of its connected components $\Gamma_{1}$, called edges, each homeomorphic to an open intervals with boundary in $\Gamma_{0}$.
Definition 4.16. \thlabel def:partial-natural-transformation-beck-chevalley A partial natural transformation $(\beta,k):F\to F^{\prime}$ is said to satisfy the weak Beck-Chevalley condition if for any $f:\mathbf{n}\to\mathbf{m}$ the following commutes: $\tikzcd\mathcal{K}^{o}(F^{\prime}_{n})\arrow[rrr,"\beta_{n}^{-1}\cap F_{f^{% \times k}}(F_{mk})"]&&&\mathcal{K}^{o}(F_{nk})\\ \mathcal{K}^{o}(F^{\prime}_{m})\arrow[u,"F^{\prime}_{f}"]\arrow[rrr,"\beta_{m}% ^{-1}"^{\prime}]&&&\mathcal{K}^{o}(F_{mk})\arrow[u,"F_{f^{\times k}}"^{\prime}]$ We say that $(\beta,k)$ satisfies the Beck-Chevalley condition if the above diagram commutes already without taking the intersection. That is $\beta_{n}^{-1}F^{\prime}_{f}=F_{f^{\times k}}\beta_{m}^{-1}$.
Definition 6.6. \thlabel def:morphism-partial-natural-transformations Let $(\beta,k),(\beta^{\prime},k^{\prime}):F\dashrightarrow F^{\prime}$ be partial natural transformations. A morphism of partial natural transformations $\Theta:(\beta,k)\to(\beta^{\prime},k^{\prime})$ is a cartesian family $\Theta_{n}\subseteq F_{nk+nk^{\prime}}$, such that for every compact open $U\subseteq F_{n}^{\prime}$ we have $\llbracket R_{\Theta_{n}}(\bar{x},\bar{y})\wedge R_{\beta_{n}^{-1}(U)}(\bar{x}% )\rrbracket\subseteq\llbracket R_{\beta_{n}^{\prime-1}(U)}(\bar{y})\rrbracket.$ Furthermore, we require for all $n$ that the following also hold: $\displaystyle\llbracket R_{\Theta_{n}}(\bar{x},\bar{y})\wedge R_{\beta_{2}^{-1% }(\llbracket x=x^{\prime}\rrbracket)}(\bar{x},\bar{x}^{\prime})\rrbracket$ $\displaystyle\subseteq\llbracket R_{\Theta_{n}}(\bar{x}^{\prime},\bar{y})\rrbracket,$ $\displaystyle\llbracket R_{\Theta_{n}}(\bar{x},\bar{y})\wedge R_{\beta_{2}^{% \prime-1}(\llbracket y=y^{\prime}\rrbracket)}(\bar{y},\bar{y}^{\prime})\rrbracket$ $\displaystyle\subseteq\llbracket R_{\Theta_{n}}(\bar{x},\bar{y}^{\prime})\rrbracket,$ $\displaystyle\llbracket\exists\bar{y}R_{\Theta_{n}}(\bar{x},\bar{y})\rrbracket$ $\displaystyle=\operatorname{dom}(\beta_{n}).$ We define vertical composition by: $(\Omega\Theta)_{n}=\llbracket\exists\bar{y}(R_{\Theta_{n}}(\bar{x},\bar{y})% \wedge R_{\Omega_{n}}(\bar{y},\bar{z}))\rrbracket.$ For horizontal composition, consider the following diagram: $\tikzcd F\arrow[rr,"{(\gamma,\ell)}",dashed,bendleft]\arrow[rr,"{(\gamma^{% \prime},\ell^{\prime})}"^{\prime},dashed,bendright]&\Omega\Downarrow&F^{\prime% }\arrow[rr,"{(\beta,k)}",dashed,bendleft]\arrow[rr,"{(\beta^{\prime},k^{\prime% })}"^{\prime},dashed,bendright]&\Theta\Downarrow&F^{\prime\prime}$ Then for all $n$: $(\Theta*\Omega)_{n}=\left\llbracket\exists\bar{y}_{1}\ldots\bar{y}_{k^{\prime}% }\left(R_{\gamma_{n(k+k^{\prime})}^{-1}(\Theta_{n})}(\bar{x}_{1},\ldots,\bar{x% }_{k},\bar{y}_{1},\ldots,\bar{y}_{k^{\prime}})\wedge\bigwedge_{i=1}^{k^{\prime% }}R_{\Omega_{n}}(\bar{y}_{i},\bar{z}_{i})\right)\right\rrbracket,$ where each $\bar{x}_{i}$ and $\bar{y}_{i}$ is of length $n\ell$ and each $\bar{z}_{i}$ is of length $n\ell^{\prime}$.
